'''''Knights of the Old Republic'' 1''' is the first issue in the [[Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic (comic series)|''Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic'']] series of [[Star Wars comic books|comic books]], which was written by [[John Jackson Miller]] and published by [[Dark Horse Comics]] as the flagship series of their overhaul of their ''[[Star Wars]]'' line for their 25th anniversary in [[2006]]. ''Commencement, Part 1'' was released on [[January 25]], [[2006]].

==Opening crawl==
{{OpeningCrawl
|name=COMMENCEMENT<br />"PART ONE"
|text=It is a time of upheaval for the galaxy. Nearly four
thousand years before the birth of Luke Skywalker, the
Mandalorian Wars have strained the OLD REPUBLIC's
resources to the breaking point.

With so many Republic forces at the front, systems in
the Outer Rim teeter on the edge of lawlessness. The
city-world of TARIS, once a thriving commercial center,
becomes a battleground for rival gangs of criminals.

On Taris, as elsewhere, the Republic relies increasingly
on JEDI KNIGHTS to maintain order. But with many
Knights, also away at war, it falls to the untried students
of the Jedi order's satellite academies to fill the gap&hellip;}}

==Plot summary==
While trying to make an illegal sale of [[Ryll/Legends|spice]] and ale, [[Marn Hierogryph]] is taken off-guard by [[Zayne Carrick]], a [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]] assigned to bring the [[Snivvian/Legends|Snivvian]] to justice. After dropping the barrels of ale on Zayne, Gryph flees by climbing up a rooftop and manages to escape by kicking Zayne off a ladder while he was he was attempting a futile Jedi [[Mind trick/Legends|mind trick]]. Zayne ends up falling into a private banquet held by the Jedi to celebrate the final Jedi training of their Padawans and is greeted by nine [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsabers]] pointed at him.

After apologizing for his Padawan, [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Lucien Draay]] makes a speech of the coming [[Jedi Trials/Legends|Jedi Trials]], while Zayne talks to his friends. Later, while discussing the cost of the damages related to his entrance with the banquet manager, Zayne sees Gryph and chases him until he is captured through [[Telekinesis/Legends|telekinesis]]. After arresting him, Zayne goes to the [[Jedi Temple/Legends|Jedi Temple]] late for the ceremony only to find his fellow students [[Padawan Massacre|murdered by their own masters]].

==Development==
[[File:Kotor_01_pg_09_low_res.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Brian Ching's original banquet scene design]]
Early on in the series' development [[Brian Ching]] soon realized that it would be hard to convey expressions for Marn Hierogryph on an [[Ortolan/Legends|Ortolan's]] mouthless face, so Miller suggested a Snivvian instead. Atiyeh and Ching developed detailed visuals for each of the series' characters, and by [[August]] 2005 at [[Wikipedia:San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con International]] in [[Wikipedia:San Diego|San Diego]], most of the first issue was done, and Miller had scripted several issues onward.<ref name="Miller 1">{{Faraway|url=comics/swknights/swkotor01.html|text=''Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic #1''}}</ref> The script for the first issue had already been completed and turned in by [[May]] 2005.<ref name="Lightsabre">{{WebCite|url=http://www.lightsabre.co.uk|text=The Lightsabre Interview: John Jackson Miller|date=2006-06-04|format=Interview|archivedate=20070709203507}}</ref> The issue was released on [[January 25]], 2006, 363 days after Miller and [[Randy Stradley]] had had their initial conversation about the series. Miller deleted Ching's preliminary drawing of the [[:File:WhatTheHeck.jpg|double-page scene]] in ''Commencement, Part 1'' from his hard drive to prevent himself from accidentally emailing it to fans, as he wanted to keep it secret until the issue's release. Ching and Miller also worked especially hard to create Carrick's and Lucien Draay's expressions for the final page of the issue.<ref name="Miller 1" />

When the series was first launched, Dark Horse was disappointed by the initial sales of #1; however, the issue soon sold out and went to a second printing. By [[June]], orders for ''Knights of the Old Republic'' had risen in numbers and was beating out ''Star Wars: Rebellion''.<ref name="Stradley DH Saddle">{{DHBoards|url=viewtopic.php?p=127639#p127639|thread=Dark Horse is Back in the Saddle|user=Randy Stradley|date=2006-05-16|time=06:01|nobackup=1}}</ref> The covers for the fist arc of the series were drawn by [[Travis Charest]], and the cover for issue #1&mdash;Carrick holding the slain Padawan Kamlin in his arms&mdash;was designed well in advance based on general plot information.<ref name="Countdown 7">{{Faraway|url=blog/2010/02/14/kotor-countdown-7-just-asked-questions|text=KOTOR Countdown #7: Just-Asked Questions, Part Two}}</ref> For the banquet scene in issue #1, Brian Ching originally depicted the banquet as a particularly busy scene with numerous details, but he scrapped it in favor of a set of panels that focused more on the five Masters and was less "boring."<ref name="Page 9 Original">{{Blogspot|subdomain=brianching|url=2006/05/kotor-1-pg-9-original.html|name=The Art of Brian Ching|text=KOTOR #1, pg 9 original}}</ref>

